Cic. de Am. z quod contra oportebat delicto dolere, correctione 961111Ie2·e.-—‹leczlit : H. 541, 33 A. & G. 288, a, Rem. The funeral pile was generally lit by the nearest relatives of the deceased. Cato here means that the son would in the ordinary course of events survive the father. At first the Romans interred their dead, but sometimes adopted the Greek custom of cremation, which is mentioned in the laws of Numa and in those of the XII. Tables. The practice of burn- ing the dead did not come into very general use till the end of the Republic (Cic. de Legg. 2, 20 3 Pliny.
